### Anything else relevant?

I tested with an older version of Angular CLI, specifically v20.0.3 (before commit [2316fe2](https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/commit/2316fe2)), and the issue did not occur there.

As a workaround, I added an additional overrides entry in `package.json` to explicitly force Prettier to use single quotes for `.ts` files:
```json
"prettier": {
    "overrides": [
      {
        "files": "*.html",
        "options": {
          "parser": "angular"
        }
      },
      {
        "files": "*.ts",
        "options": {
          "singleQuote": true
        }
      }
    ]
  }
```

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/6fb00327-1580-4618-89d3-0fd7c858860c)

This seems to restore the expected formatting behavior for TypeScript files, though Iâ€™m not certain whether this workaround could introduce unintended side effects. Further testing would be helpful.

### Feature Description

I want to be able to use Angular's directive composition API with the sorting behavior made available through the `MatSort` directive. As of this writing, the directive is not standalone, so that is impossible.

### Use Case

Rather than setting the sort properties manually in the template, consumers could make directives which use `hostDirectives` to configure sorting behavior from the template, like this:

```
@Directive({
  selector: '[sortUsingConfig]',
  hostDirectives: [{ 
     directive: MatSort, 
  ],
  standalone: true,
})
export class SortUsingConfigDirective implements OnInit {
  @Input('sortUsingConfig') config: [some config];

  private sortDirective= inject(MatSort);

  ngOnInit() {
    this.sortDirective = {
      ...this.sortDirective,
      start: config.start,
      disableClear: config.disableClear
    };
  }
}

HTML
<table *sortUsingConfig="config">
